1
00:00:01,384 --> 00:00:03,797
[woman screaming]

2
00:00:12,187 --> 00:00:14,178
[screaming continues]

3
00:00:23,490 --> 00:00:25,823
[screaming continues]

4
00:00:41,341 --> 00:00:44,175
[screaming continues]

5
00:00:55,814 --> 00:00:57,646
[man narrating]
<i>To Edgar Allan Poe,</i>

6
00:00:57,732 --> 00:01:00,816
<i>whose stories have inspired
this motion picture.</i>

7
00:01:11,371 --> 00:01:13,783
[chorus singing in Latin]

8
00:01:31,390 --> 00:01:34,008
[singing continues]

9
00:01:44,863 --> 00:01:47,196
[woman] Is that an accusation,
Mr. Pike?

10
00:01:48,491 --> 00:01:50,483
Is that some sort of
an accusation?

11
00:01:53,538 --> 00:01:55,825
Is that some sort of
an accusation, Mr. Pike?

12
00:01:55,915 --> 00:01:59,408
- [man] What'd you say?
- Nothing. Nothing.

13
00:01:59,502 --> 00:02:02,495
- I thought you said something.
- No.

14
00:02:04,341 --> 00:02:06,298
I was just talking to myself.
It's nothing.

15
00:02:32,285 --> 00:02:34,277
[clock ticking]

16
00:02:38,958 --> 00:02:42,668
He's liquidating a substantial
number of his assets here.

17
00:02:44,047 --> 00:02:48,883
This represents 15,
possibly 20 percent of his holdings.

18
00:02:48,968 --> 00:02:53,178
I wouldn't know. Ernie has never talked
to me much about business.

19
00:02:53,264 --> 00:02:55,256
Perhaps if he'd be willing
to wait until...

20
00:02:55,350 --> 00:02:57,012
He can't wait, Mr. Pike.

21
00:02:57,102 --> 00:03:00,891
The doctors give him three weeks.
Six at the most.

22
00:03:01,398 --> 00:03:03,731
Ernie wants this done now.

23
00:03:03,817 --> 00:03:06,275
With all the proceeds going to you.

24
00:03:06,361 --> 00:03:09,069
- That's right.
- Bad timing.

25
00:03:09,155 --> 00:03:13,149
The market price on some of these stocks
is lower than it's been in years.

26
00:03:14,035 --> 00:03:17,028
Why doesn't he simply put
these assets in your name?

27
00:03:17,122 --> 00:03:21,162
I don't need assets, Mr. Pike.
I need dollars to live on.

28
00:03:21,251 --> 00:03:24,915
You've been remembered,
quite generously, in the will.

29
00:03:25,004 --> 00:03:28,168
And how long will it take
to settle the estate, Mr. Pike?

30
00:03:28,675 --> 00:03:31,383
Eighteen months. Two years.

31
00:03:31,469 --> 00:03:33,631
- Depending on...
- What do I do while I'm waiting?

32
00:03:33,722 --> 00:03:35,384
Take a job as a waitress?

33
00:03:35,890 --> 00:03:37,927
I'm not society, Mr. Pike.

34
00:03:38,017 --> 00:03:39,679
I have nothing of my own.

35
00:03:40,978 --> 00:03:44,518
I was a flight attendant
that Ernie brought home off the red-eye...

36
00:03:44,607 --> 00:03:48,692
to the shock and dismay of you
and everyone else in this town.

37
00:03:48,778 --> 00:03:51,816
I married a rich, old man.

38
00:03:51,906 --> 00:03:55,866
I let him use me...
for pleasure and for show.

39
00:03:57,871 --> 00:04:00,454
Now I'm going to let him
pay me for my services.

40
00:04:00,540 --> 00:04:03,499
[clock chiming]

41
00:04:18,099 --> 00:04:20,341
This is Ernest's signature?

42
00:04:20,435 --> 00:04:22,597
Is that some sort of
an accusation, Mr. Pike?

43
00:04:34,866 --> 00:04:37,279
Hello, Ernie. Yes.

44
00:04:38,912 --> 00:04:41,154
Yes. I'm here with Steven Pike.

45
00:04:41,247 --> 00:04:45,082
I gave him the papers.
I don't think he likes it very much.

46
00:04:46,336 --> 00:04:48,293
- [clock ticking]
- Well...

47
00:04:49,005 --> 00:04:50,462
are you sure you're up to it?

48
00:04:52,425 --> 00:04:54,132
All right. I'll put him on.

49
00:05:00,099 --> 00:05:02,762
[ticking continues]

50
00:05:02,852 --> 00:05:06,641
- Hello, Ernest.
- [Ernest] <i>Hello, Steven.</i>

51
00:05:07,190 --> 00:05:10,058
How are you feeling?
How's the pain?

52
00:05:10,151 --> 00:05:12,017
Are you feeling much pain?

53
00:05:12,111 --> 00:05:15,024
[Ernest] <i>No. No pain.</i>

54
00:05:15,448 --> 00:05:16,448
[Pike] Listen, Ernest.

55
00:05:17,408 --> 00:05:20,992
I have these papers here,
the ones you sent.

56
00:05:21,371 --> 00:05:22,532
<i>Yes?</i>

57
00:05:23,540 --> 00:05:26,032
Are you sure
you want to do this?

58
00:05:26,125 --> 00:05:28,082
Have you thought this through?

59
00:05:28,169 --> 00:05:31,832
<i>Yes. I want to do it,
Steven.</i>

60
00:05:31,923 --> 00:05:34,165
<i>I owe it to Jessica.</i>

61
00:05:34,884 --> 00:05:36,420
- [man] <i>Hello?</i>
- Yes?

62
00:05:36,511 --> 00:05:39,754
<i>- Who is this?</i>
- I'm Steven Pike, Mr. Valdemar's attorney.

63
00:05:39,848 --> 00:05:42,340
<i>Bob Hoffman, Mr. Pike.
I'm Ernie's doctor.</i>

64
00:05:42,433 --> 00:05:46,017
<i>Look. Is all this really necessary?
Uh, Ernie's...</i>

65
00:05:46,104 --> 00:05:47,845
<i>Well, he needs as much rest
as he can get.</i>

66
00:05:47,939 --> 00:05:49,771
<i>So, unless this is
something really urgent...</i>

67
00:05:49,858 --> 00:05:55,570
Well, Ernest is asking me
to do something a bit, uh, unorthodox.

68
00:05:55,655 --> 00:05:59,239
Something that's, uh,
very unlike him to do.

69
00:05:59,325 --> 00:06:03,945
<i>People with Ernest's prognosis will often
do surprising things, Mr. Pike.</i>

70
00:06:04,038 --> 00:06:06,405
<i>I can assure you his mind
is as sharp as ever.</i>

71
00:06:06,499 --> 00:06:09,037
I see. I see.
Thank you, Doctor. I...

72
00:06:09,127 --> 00:06:11,585
I hope I haven't disturbed him
too much.

73
00:06:11,671 --> 00:06:13,412
<i>I just don't want him agitated.
That's all.</i>

74
00:06:13,506 --> 00:06:16,670
<i>- I'm sure you understand.</i>
- [Pike] Yes. Yes, of course. Yes, uh...

75
00:06:16,759 --> 00:06:19,001
- Good-bye, Doctor.
<i>- Good-bye.</i>

76
00:06:26,185 --> 00:06:27,847
I'll prepare the necessary forms

77
00:06:27,937 --> 00:06:29,929
and mail them to you
for Ernest's signature.

78
00:06:30,023 --> 00:06:32,982
Well, I wouldn't want any delays.
I'll stop by and pick them up.

79
00:06:33,610 --> 00:06:36,023
Tomorrow morning.
They'll be ready, I hope?

80
00:06:37,488 --> 00:06:39,605
- They'll be ready.
- Thank you.

81
00:06:40,533 --> 00:06:42,115
Have a nice day, Mr. Pike.

82
00:07:20,490 --> 00:07:22,482
[ice cubes rattling]

83
00:07:54,190 --> 00:07:56,182
- [ticking]
- [machine beeping]

84
00:08:02,824 --> 00:08:05,066
- God, he's still...
- Still under.

85
00:08:06,077 --> 00:08:08,740
Still completely at my command.

86
00:08:08,830 --> 00:08:10,822
- [ticking continues]
- [beeping continues]

87
00:08:11,666 --> 00:08:13,532
- Valdemar.
- [dial tone]

88
00:08:13,626 --> 00:08:15,117
Repeat these words.

89
00:08:16,671 --> 00:08:17,912
I want to do it.

90
00:08:18,756 --> 00:08:20,418
I owe it to JJessica.

91
00:08:20,967 --> 00:08:24,927
I want to do it.
I owe it to Jessica.

92
00:08:25,888 --> 00:08:27,754
- Wake him up.
- [handset settles in cradle]

93
00:08:27,849 --> 00:08:31,513
To the pain?
To the realization that he's dying?

94
00:08:32,937 --> 00:08:34,678
He's better off where he is.

95
00:08:37,482 --> 00:08:38,563
Besides,

96
00:08:39,610 --> 00:08:41,351
I thought if we let him sleep,

97
00:08:42,280 --> 00:08:45,773
we might be able to have some time,
liquidate a few assets of our own.

98
00:08:45,867 --> 00:08:48,655
- Robert! What if he...
- What? What if he hears me?

99
00:08:48,745 --> 00:08:50,407
Well, I'm sure he can. Valdemar.

100
00:08:50,955 --> 00:08:52,947
- Do you hear me?
- Yes.

101
00:08:53,875 --> 00:08:56,663
- I hear you.
- Fascinating.

102
00:08:56,753 --> 00:09:00,372
Somewhere deep in his consciousness
he knows exactly what we're doing to him.

103
00:09:01,049 --> 00:09:03,507
But when I wake him,
it'll all disappear.

104
00:09:05,136 --> 00:09:07,002
Like the fragments of a dream.

105
00:09:07,096 --> 00:09:08,507
I don't find it fascinating.

106
00:09:10,266 --> 00:09:11,347
It's morbid.

107
00:09:13,061 --> 00:09:14,097
Frightening.

108
00:09:14,187 --> 00:09:16,725
- [beeping continues]
- [ticking continues]

109
00:09:17,982 --> 00:09:20,895
I'm not as...
vindictive as you are.

110
00:09:20,985 --> 00:09:22,692
I don't take
any pleasure out of this.

111
00:09:23,696 --> 00:09:28,066
He's a ruthless old man who treats people
as if they were possessions.

112
00:09:28,159 --> 00:09:31,277
He spent his life taking whatever
he wanted without a care for anyone else.

113
00:09:31,370 --> 00:09:35,785
He took you away from me.
Vindictive? Yes. Yes, I am vindictive.

114
00:09:35,875 --> 00:09:37,787
He didn't take me.
I went.

115
00:09:37,877 --> 00:09:39,117
He didn't know
I was seeing you.

116
00:09:39,170 --> 00:09:41,065
He doesn't even realize
we knew each other bef...

117
00:09:41,089 --> 00:09:45,049
- I want you back, Jess.
- Robert. Please. I can't.

118
00:09:45,134 --> 00:09:46,841
Not now. I couldn't.

119
00:09:48,304 --> 00:09:50,717
I-I'm having a very
difficult time with this. I...

120
00:09:51,682 --> 00:09:56,677
I need you to try to be sensitive to that,
try to understand how hard this is for me.

121
00:09:57,688 --> 00:10:00,709
- If you want me to go through with it...
- You already have gone through with this.

122
00:10:00,733 --> 00:10:02,349
There's no turning back anymore.

123
00:10:02,443 --> 00:10:05,443
What are you gonna tell Mr. Pike?
"Oh, this has all been a misunderstanding.

124
00:10:05,863 --> 00:10:07,820
I didn't realize my husband
was under hypnosis

125
00:10:07,907 --> 00:10:09,648
when I asked him to sign
the papers."

126
00:10:09,742 --> 00:10:12,109
You won't like it in prison, Jessica.
The food's awful.

127
00:10:14,330 --> 00:10:16,242
And let's call a spade a spade, all right?

128
00:10:16,332 --> 00:10:19,496
This was your idea, not mine.
I was willing to wait.

129
00:10:19,585 --> 00:10:22,874
I just wanted us to be together again,
but that wasn't good enough, was it?

130
00:10:22,964 --> 00:10:25,081
Not after you got a taste
of what it was to be rich.

131
00:10:25,174 --> 00:10:27,111
You're going to pretend
you don't care about the money?

132
00:10:27,135 --> 00:10:28,501
No. Of course I want the money,

133
00:10:28,594 --> 00:10:31,007
but I want you too,
and I thought you wanted me.

134
00:10:31,097 --> 00:10:32,213
I do.

135
00:10:34,767 --> 00:10:36,349
Robert, I do. Uh...

136
00:10:37,061 --> 00:10:38,518
It's just difficult...

137
00:10:39,063 --> 00:10:41,771
Difficult to care about someone
you know is a thief?

138
00:10:43,985 --> 00:10:44,985
I know.

139
00:10:46,195 --> 00:10:47,652
I have the same problem.

140
00:10:56,205 --> 00:10:57,616
- [beeping]
- [ticking stops]

141
00:10:57,707 --> 00:11:01,075
Valdemar.
I'm going to wake you now.

142
00:11:02,336 --> 00:11:03,793
When I count to five,

143
00:11:04,297 --> 00:11:07,461
you will be completely awake
and alert.

144
00:11:08,759 --> 00:11:09,759
One.

145
00:11:10,678 --> 00:11:12,510
You will not remember anything.

146
00:11:13,681 --> 00:11:17,345
Two. You're starting
to regain your senses.

147
00:11:18,477 --> 00:11:21,811
Three. Starting to see the room.

148
00:11:21,898 --> 00:11:23,514
Starting to see me.

149
00:11:25,026 --> 00:11:26,107
Four.

150
00:11:27,028 --> 00:11:30,647
[Ernest] Oh, God! The pain!

151
00:11:30,740 --> 00:11:32,322
[screaming]

152
00:11:32,408 --> 00:11:34,115
God. Can't you help him?

153
00:11:34,911 --> 00:11:37,244
He'll be asleep soon.
He's had his injection.

154
00:11:37,330 --> 00:11:38,616
There's not much else I can do.

155
00:11:38,706 --> 00:11:41,949
[sighs] You could stay with him.
That's what you're being paid for.

156
00:11:42,043 --> 00:11:43,909
You should have him in a hospital.

157
00:11:44,587 --> 00:11:46,499
A man in his advanced state.

158
00:11:46,964 --> 00:11:50,128
Keeping him at home.
I have never seen anything like it.

159
00:11:50,218 --> 00:11:52,881
In all my years of nursing,
I've never seen anything like it.

160
00:11:53,262 --> 00:11:56,255
[Ernest moaning]

161
00:12:03,064 --> 00:12:06,648
[Ernest] Where is
that bitch of a wife of mine?

162
00:12:08,486 --> 00:12:09,897
Where is she?

163
00:12:10,446 --> 00:12:13,029
Out spending my money.

164
00:12:14,283 --> 00:12:16,866
Where is she? Where...

165
00:12:18,663 --> 00:12:20,029
Jessica!

166
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:22,326
Jessica!

167
00:12:26,629 --> 00:12:28,165
Jessica!

168
00:12:35,638 --> 00:12:37,095
Jessica!

169
00:12:37,181 --> 00:12:41,016
[TV: loud noises]

170
00:12:45,314 --> 00:12:48,022
Two of the money market accounts
are with the local bank.

171
00:12:48,109 --> 00:12:52,194
Those funds are available to you now.
See Mr. Pratt.

172
00:12:52,655 --> 00:12:54,897
The rest is going to take some time.

173
00:12:55,783 --> 00:12:58,150
- How much time?
- Paperwork, mails,

174
00:12:58,244 --> 00:13:00,361
out-of-town checks
will have to clear.

175
00:13:00,955 --> 00:13:02,446
Two to three weeks.

176
00:13:07,211 --> 00:13:09,294
If anything should happen to Ernest,

177
00:13:09,380 --> 00:13:11,747
you'll have a hard time collecting,
I'm afraid.

178
00:13:12,383 --> 00:13:14,545
So do your best to keep him alive,
won't you?

179
00:13:14,635 --> 00:13:17,969
- I'll do my best.
- I'm sure you will.

180
00:13:27,023 --> 00:13:30,983
This is quite a lot to be walking
around with in cash, Mrs. Valdemar.

181
00:13:31,068 --> 00:13:33,310
Now, we do offer
a liquid asset account

182
00:13:33,404 --> 00:13:35,270
that would allow you
to withdraw any amount...

183
00:13:35,364 --> 00:13:37,026
I'll be wanting to talk
to you about that.

184
00:13:37,116 --> 00:13:40,609
I'll be coming into quite a large sum
in the next few weeks.

185
00:13:40,703 --> 00:13:42,660
Something over three million,
I'm told.

186
00:13:43,706 --> 00:13:47,540
And, of course, I'll be wanting to put it
someplace where it will be safe.

187
00:13:48,002 --> 00:13:51,712
But this... I have a need
for this in cash.

188
00:13:51,797 --> 00:13:53,754
Whatever you say,
Mrs. Valdemar.

189
00:13:53,841 --> 00:13:56,128
Whenever you're ready,
just give me a call.

190
00:13:56,218 --> 00:13:59,006
We're, uh...
We're here to please.

191
00:14:13,944 --> 00:14:15,936
[whirring]

192
00:14:20,993 --> 00:14:22,700
That's good enough, Martha. You can go.

193
00:14:22,787 --> 00:14:25,780
- We've not done the upstairs yet, Mrs. V.
- It doesn't need to be done.

194
00:14:25,873 --> 00:14:28,536
It's fine. Really.
You can get it next time.

195
00:14:28,626 --> 00:14:30,162
If you say so, mum.

196
00:14:30,252 --> 00:14:33,915
All right, people.
Let's pack it up. We're leaving.

197
00:14:34,006 --> 00:14:37,124
Mr. V seems in
a bad way today, mum.

198
00:14:37,843 --> 00:14:40,551
Yes. He's, uh, been bad
for some time now.

199
00:14:40,638 --> 00:14:44,473
Poor old soul. Night nurse left,
and I didn't know what to do.

200
00:14:44,558 --> 00:14:46,675
I'm sorry. I didn't expect
to be gone so long.

201
00:14:46,769 --> 00:14:49,182
That's all right.
Doctor's with him now.

202
00:14:49,271 --> 00:14:51,012
Oh, he's here? Good.

203
00:14:59,365 --> 00:15:01,357
[door closes]

204
00:15:35,067 --> 00:15:37,480
- [machine beeping]
- [ticking]

205
00:15:37,570 --> 00:15:41,655
[Robert] Sign your name, Valdemar.
Sign your name on the line.

206
00:15:53,252 --> 00:15:54,834
Again, Valdemar.

207
00:15:57,965 --> 00:15:59,797
Here. On the line.

208
00:16:00,342 --> 00:16:01,753
Sign your name again.

209
00:16:01,844 --> 00:16:04,461
[beeping continues]

210
00:16:20,362 --> 00:16:21,773
Done.

211
00:16:21,864 --> 00:16:23,901
- Is he...
- Still under.

212
00:16:26,285 --> 00:16:27,366
Come here.

213
00:16:29,538 --> 00:16:31,245
Are you sure you want to?

214
00:16:34,001 --> 00:16:35,333
Yes.

215
00:16:41,133 --> 00:16:42,669
What did you put
in the safe, Jesse?

216
00:16:42,760 --> 00:16:44,797
[chuckles]
The safe?

217
00:16:46,055 --> 00:16:47,421
When you came in.

218
00:16:48,098 --> 00:16:50,841
I saw you put something
in the safe. What was it?

219
00:16:50,935 --> 00:16:52,176
[Jessica] Money.

220
00:16:53,729 --> 00:16:56,436
- You got the money.
- Some.

221
00:16:58,150 --> 00:17:00,983
- Just a little.
- How much is a little?

222
00:17:02,029 --> 00:17:05,146
[Jessica] I don't know.
A few thousand.

223
00:17:07,617 --> 00:17:09,575
None of it mine, I suppose.

224
00:17:10,246 --> 00:17:12,157
I'll have the rest in
a few weeks.

225
00:17:12,248 --> 00:17:14,830
Oh. Nothing for me
until the job is finished.

226
00:17:14,916 --> 00:17:16,954
- Is that it?
- [chuckles]

227
00:17:17,502 --> 00:17:18,993
That's not fair.

228
00:17:20,297 --> 00:17:22,880
I haven't gotten anything
out of this, Jess.

229
00:17:22,967 --> 00:17:24,252
Soon.

230
00:17:25,261 --> 00:17:26,797
In a few weeks.

231
00:17:28,097 --> 00:17:29,963
In a few weeks we'll have it all.

232
00:17:31,141 --> 00:17:33,633
Just think of it.
A million dollars.

233
00:17:35,104 --> 00:17:37,642
A million dollars
for us to share.

234
00:17:43,153 --> 00:17:44,985
Mine in cash.
Remember?

235
00:17:46,949 --> 00:17:48,360
No checks.

236
00:17:49,577 --> 00:17:52,866
- Nothing with my name on it.
- Ah, don't worry.

237
00:17:53,622 --> 00:17:57,081
- Nothing to connect us.
- There's nothing to connect us.

238
00:17:58,669 --> 00:18:00,877
Nothing at all to connect us.

239
00:18:03,215 --> 00:18:05,207
[machine beeping]

240
00:18:09,054 --> 00:18:10,261
It's Ernest.

241
00:18:20,232 --> 00:18:23,020
[steady beep]

242
00:18:38,584 --> 00:18:39,950
Oh, my God.

243
00:18:40,044 --> 00:18:42,878
